<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-second-derivative-test-and-saddle-points">
	<title>The Second Derivative Test</title>

	<subsection>
		<title>The Two Variable Second Derivative Test</title>

		<p>
			As in single-variable calculus, a critical point of a function is not necessarily a local extremum. This happens at a <em>saddle point</em>.
		</p>

		<definition>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A critical point of a function which is not a local minimum or local maximum is called a <term>saddle point</term>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<figure>
			<caption>A saddle point at the origin of the function <m>f(x,y) = y^2 - x^2</m>. Note that along the <m>x</m>-axis (<m>y = 0</m>), the function has a global maximum at <m>x = 0</m>, while along the <m>y</m>-axis (<m>x = 0</m>), the function has a global minimum at <m>y = 0</m>. This combination of maximum in one direction and minimum in another is characteristic of saddle points.</caption>
			<image source="calc3-fig-4-48.png" width="50%"/>
		</figure>

		<p>
			The <em>second derivative test</em> provides a method for determining whether an local extremum occurs at a critical point of a function. The test is more complicated for two variable functions than the second derivative test for functions of a single variable, given that there are <em>four</em> second  derivatives rather than just one derivative.
		</p>

		<theorem>
			<title>The Two Variable Second Derivative Test</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>f(x,y)</m> is a scalar-function of two variables, and the first and second derivatives of <m>f</m> are continuous on a disk containing some critical point <m>(a,b)</m> for <m>f</m> Define the <term>discriminant</term>
					<me>
						D(a,b) = f_{xx}(a,b)f_{yy}(a,b) - f_{xy}(a,b)^2
					</me>
					Then:
				</p>

				<ul>
					<li>If <m>D(a,b) > 0</m> and <m>f_{xx}(a,b) > 0</m>, then <m>(a,b)</m> is a <em>local minimum</em> of <m>f</m>.</li>

					<li>If <m>D(a,b) > 0</m> and <m>f_{xx}(a,b) \lt 0</m>, then <m>(a,b)</m> is a <em>local maximum</em> of <m>f</m>.</li>

					<li>If <m>D(a,b) \lt 0</m>, then <m>(a,b)</m> is a <em>saddle point</em>.</li>

					<li>If <m>D(a, b) = 0</m>, then the test does not tell us whether <m>(a,b)</m> is a local extremum.</li>
				</ul>
			</statement>
		</theorem>

		<remark>
			<p>
				From our current perspective, the second derivative test is quite mysterious. It seems unclear why the discriminant <m>D</m> is able to detect local extrema. We will later see in <xref ref="act-10-1-second-derivative-test-two-variables"/>, using our knowledge of linear algebra from <xref ref="ch-eigenvectors"/>, in particular the theory of eigenvalues, <em>why</em> the second derivative test detects local extrema, and also determine an analogue of the second derivative test for functions of more than two variables.
			</p>
		</remark>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use the second derivative test to determine if the critical point <m>(1,-2)</m> of <m>f(x,y) = x^2 + y^2 - 2x + 4y</m> found earlier is a local maximum, a local minimum, or a saddle point.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					We apply the second derivative test. We compute the second-order partial derivatives of <m>f</m>. We calculate that
					<me>
						f_{xx}(x,y) = 2 \quad f_{yy} = 2 \quad\text{and} \quad f_{xy}(x,y) = 0
					</me>.
					So the discriminant is the constant function
					<me>D = f_{xx} f_{yy} - f_{xy}^2 = (2)(2) - (0)^2 = 4</me>.
					Since the discriminant is positive, by the second derivative test, the critical point <m>(1,-2)</m> is a local minimum.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use the second derivative test to analyze the critical point <m>(0,0)</m> of <m>f(x,y) = x^2 - y^2</m> found earlier.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					We need to compute the second-order partial derivatives:
					<me>
						f_{xx} = 2 \quad f_{yy} = -2 \quad \text{and} \quad f_{xy} = 0
					</me>.
					So the discriminant is also the constant function
					<me>
						D = f_{xx} f_{yy} - f_{xy}^2 = (2)(-2) - (0)^2 = -4
					</me>.
					Since the discriminant is negative, the second derivative test tells us that <m>(0,0)</m> is a <em>saddle point</em> of <m>f</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find all local maxima, local minima, and saddle points for the function
					<me>f(x,y) = x^2 + xy + y^2 - 6x + 6</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					We begin by finding the critical points of <m>f</m>. We calculate that
					<me>
						f_x(x,y) = 2x + y + 6 \quad\text{and}\quad f_y(x,y) = x + 2y
					</me>.
					So the critical points satisfy both <m>2x + y + 6 = 0</m> and <m>x + 2y = 0</m>. The second equation is equivalent to <m>x = -2y</m>, and substituting this equation into the first gives <m>3y = 6</m>, so that the only critical point is <m>(-4,2)</m>.
				</p>

				<p>
					To classify this critical point, we apply the second derivative test. We calculate that
					<me>
						f_{xx}(x,y) = 2 \quad f_{yy} = 2 \quad\text{and}\quad f_{xy} = 1
					</me>.
					So the discriminant is the constant function
					<me>
						D = f_{xx} f_{yy} - f_{xy}^2 = (2)(2) - (1)^2 = 3
					</me>.
					Since the discriminant is positive, and <m>f_{xx}</m> is positive, this tells us that the critical point <m>(-4,2)</m> is a local minimum.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

		<p>
			In the previous examples, the discriminant of the functions were constant because <m>f</m> was a quadratic function. Let us consider an example where the discriminant is non-constant.
		</p>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find all local maxima, local minima, and saddle points for the function <m>f(x,y) = x^3 + y^2 + 2xy - 4x - 3y + 5</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					We begin by finding the critical point. We calculate that
					<me>
						f_x(x,y) = 3x^2 + 2y - 4 \quad\text{and}\quad f_y(x,y) = 2y + 2x - 3
					</me>.
					Setting both equal to zero gives the pair of equations
					<me>
						3x^2 + 2y - 4 = 0 \quad\text{and}\quad 2y + 2x - 3 = 0
					</me>.
					We solve the second equation for <m>y</m>, i.e. that <m>y = 3/2 - x</m>, and then substitute this into the first equation, which leads to the equation <me>3x^2 + 2(3/2 - x) - 4 = 0</me>, which simplifies to the quadratic equation
					<me>
						3x^2 - 2x - 1 = 0
					</me>.
					The quadratic equation tells us that the roots of this equation are given by the formula
					<me>
						x = \frac{-(-2) \pm \sqrt{(-2)^2 - 4 (3)(-1)}}{2(3)} = 1/3 \pm \frac{\sqrt{16}}{6} = 1/3 \pm 2/3
					</me>.
					So <m>x = 1</m> or <m>x = -1/3</m>. For each such <m>x</m>, setting <m>y = 3/2 - x</m> gives us a critical point for <m>f</m>, so <m>f</m> has two critical points, i.e. <m>(1,1/2)</m> and <m>(-1/3,11/6)</m>.
				</p>

				<p>
					To apply the second derivative test to each critical point, we calculate the discriminant of <m>f</m>. We find that
					<me>
						f_{xx} = 6x \quad f_{yy} = 2 \quad \text{and}\quad f_{xy} = 2
					</me>.
					So the discriminant is the function
					<me>
						D(x,y) = f_{xx}(x,y) f_{yy}(x,y) - f_{xy}(x,y)^2 = (6x)(2) - (2)^2 = 12x - 4
					</me>.
					So
					<me>
						D(1,1/2) = 12(1) - 4 = 8 \quad\text{and}\quad D(-1/3,11/6) = 12(-1/3) - 4 = -8
					</me>.
					Since <m>D(1,1/2)</m> is positive, and <m>f_{xx}(1,1/2) = 6</m> is positive, the critical point <m>(1,1/2)</m> is a local minimum of the function <m>f</m>. Since <m>D(-1/3,11/6)</m> is negative, this tells us that <m>(-1/3,11/6)</m> is a saddle point of the function <m>f</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

		<remark>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The following activity explains why we only look at <m>f_{xx}</m> in the first two cases of the second derivative test.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</remark>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					True or False: If <m>D > 0</m>, then <m>f_{xx}</m> and <m>f_{yy}</m> have the same sign.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					True. If <m>D = f_{xx}f_{yy} - (f_{xy})^2 > 0</m>, then <m>f_{xx}f_{yy} > (f_{xy})^2 \geq 0</m>, so <m>f_{xx} f_{yy} > 0</m>. Since <m>f_{xx} f_{yy}</m> is positive, this implies either both <m>f_{xx}</m> and <m>f_{yy}</m> are positive, or both <m>f_{xx}</m> and <m>f_{yy}</m> are negative. SO <m>f_{xx}</m> and <m>f_{yy}</m> always have the same sign when the discriminant is positive.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Saddle Points</title>

		<theorem>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>f</m> is a function with continuous second derivatives, then a point <m>\mathbf{a}</m> is a saddle point if and only if there are two lines through <m>\mathbf{a}</m> such that on one line, <m>f</m> is a local minimum when restricted to this line, and restricted to the other line, <m>f</m> is a local maximum.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</theorem>

		<p>
			As an example, the function <m>f(x,y) = x^2 - y^2</m> has a saddle point at <m>(0,0)</m>, because restricted to the line <m>y = 0</m>, <m>f(x,0) = x^2</m>, which has a local minimum at <m>x = 0</m>, whereas on the line <m>x = 0</m>, <m>f(0,y) = -y^2</m> has a local maximum. See <xref ref="fig-10-1-saddle-point-exampe"/> for a contour plot of this function.
		</p>

		<p>
			Because a saddle point is both a local maximum and minimum when restricted to two lines, it's shape tends to resemble a horse's saddle, hence the term.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-10-1-saddle-point-exampe">
			<caption>A contour plot of <m>f(x,y) = x^2 - y^2</m>. From: Stanford's MATH 51 textbook</caption>
			<image source="math51-fig-10-2-2.png" width="70%"/>
		</figure>

		<remark>
			<statement>
				<p>
					More formally, if the lines are given in parametric form by <m>\{ \mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{d}_1 \}</m> and <m>\{ \mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{d}_2 \}</m>, then we have verified the function has a saddle point if the function
					<me>g(t) = f(\mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{d}_1)</me>
					has a local maximum at <m>t = 0</m>, and the function
					<me>h(t) = f(\mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{d}_2)</me>
					has a local minimum at <m>t = 0</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</remark>

		<figure>
			<caption>At a saddle point, a local minimum over y= 0 and local maximum over x= 0. From: Stanford's MATH 51 textbook</caption>
			<image source="math51-fig-26-1-5.png" width="100%"/>
		</figure>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each point in the figure below, indicate whether it is a local maximum, a local minimum, or a saddle point.
				</p>

				<figure>
					<caption>A contour plot with a variety of types of critical points. From: Stanford's MATH 51 textbook</caption>
					<image source="math51-fig-10-2-6.png" width="70%"/>
				</figure>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					If we look at the collection of nested ovals centered on <m>S</m>, and inspect the numerical values labeling the level sets, we see those numbers are strictly increasing. These ovals seem to be honing in on a point <m>S</m> that is a local maximum. Likewise, the collection of nested ovals near <m>P</m> have function values going in a decreasing direction, suggesting <m>P</m> is a local minimum. We also see saddle points at <m>R</m> and <m>Q</m>. As we move away from <m>R</m> in the north-east direction, the function value increases, whereas moving away in the south-east direction causes the function value to decrease. Near saddle points, the contour plot forms an "X" shape dividing the space into <m>4</m> regions. Function values increase in one pair of opposite regions and decrease in the other pair. Near local extrema, level sets form oval shapes resembling ellipses.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

	</subsection>
</section>